  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4a6b8d0e2f4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software QA documentation demonstrates version control, regression testing, and audit trail for all simulation scripts and pre/post-processing routines.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2, DePuy Synthes validated solver) operate under documented software quality management systems. Version-controlled repositories with tagged releases, automated regression test suites covering >90% of model-relevant code paths, and change-control records are on file. Achieves Gradation 3 — formal SQA plan with independent review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification demonstrates correct implementation of governing equations through benchmark problems with known analytical solutions.",
      "rationale": "Each solver was exercised against NAFEMS benchmark set LE1 (plane stress elliptic membrane), LE10 (thick plate pressure), and a custom cantilever beam problem with closed-form Euler-Bernoulli solution. Relative errors in displacement and stress norms were below 0.5% for all benchmarks, confirming correct equation implementation at Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates QoI change of less than 2% between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation applied to estimate discretization uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh densities (coarse ~85k elements, medium ~340k, fine ~1.36M) were evaluated for all three QoIs. Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values below 1.8% for stiffness and yield force, and 2.0% for force at 40 mm. The medium mesh was selected for production runs, providing a discretization uncertainty contribution of ±1.4% to the total uncertainty budget. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver residual tolerances, iteration convergence, and round-off error contributions documented and shown to be negligible relative to QoI uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "The assessment team concluded that numerical solver error does not apply to this COU because all three codes are well-established commercial or government-validated solvers with published verification records, and the quasi-static linear-elastic regime of the F1717 test eliminates iterative nonlinear convergence concerns. Accordingly, no formal evaluation of solver residuals, tolerance sensitivity, or floating-point round-off was conducted and no requiredLevel or achievedLevel has been assigned. This reasoning conflates 'not-applicable' (which would require documented justification that the factor genuinely cannot influence the QoI) with a decision to simply forgo assessment — leaving the factor in a not-assessed state at modelRiskLevel 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented review process confirms that model inputs, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts were independently checked by a second analyst.",
      "rationale": "All model setup files (geometry assignments, material property tables, boundary condition scripts, and load application routines) were independently reviewed by a second qualified analyst not involved in original setup. Discrepancies identified during review were resolved and re-checked before production runs. Gradation 2 achieved through documented peer review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form assumptions (material constitutive law, contact formulation, geometric representation) are documented and justified relative to the physical phenomena governing the COU.",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw construct is modeled with isotropic linear-elastic Ti-6Al-4V (E=114 GPa, ν=0.34) consistent with ASTM F1472 material characterization. Frictional contact (μ=0.15) is applied at screw-rod interface using penalty formulation. Geometric simplifications (thread root approximated as smooth fillet, set-screw torque pre-load represented as equivalent axial preload) are documented with sensitivity analyses showing <3% effect on QoIs. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model input parameters are traceable to measurements or published data; parameter uncertainty is quantified and propagated to QoI uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon testing (N=5 coupons, Ti-6Al-4V, same heat as test constructs). Geometric dimensions measured via CMM on 3 representative screws and rods; tolerances incorporated as uniform distributions in uncertainty propagation. Monte Carlo propagation (N=5000 samples) yielded combined input uncertainty contribution of ±2.1% on stiffness QoI. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test samples are representative of the modeled geometry and material; sample-to-sample variability is characterized.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs assembled from production-representative components (same design revision, same material lot as the FEA model). CMM measurements confirmed dimensional conformance. Sample variability in stiffness (CV=4.2%) and yield force (CV=5.1%) fully characterized and incorporated into validation uncertainty. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions (loading rate, fixture alignment, environmental conditions) are documented, controlled, and matched in the simulation.",
      "rationale": "ASTM F1717 protocol followed at both laboratories; load frame calibration records and fixture alignment measurements on file. However, testing was conducted at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min) without rate sensitivity investigation, and a single fixture offset angle was used. The simulation boundary conditions match the tested conditions, but the absence of multi-condition testing limits the factor to Gradation 2 — below the required level of 3 for this modelRiskLevel. This is the known gap identified in the COU description."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters are demonstrably equivalent to those used in the validation experiments; any differences are quantified.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table maps each FEA input (material properties, geometry, pre-load, boundary conditions) to its experimental counterpart with traceability references. Differences identified: (1) thread root geometry simplified — sensitivity <1.5% on stiffness; (2) polyaxial screw head modeled as rigid — sensitivity <2.3% on yield force. Both within acceptance bounds. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) applied to all QoIs; acceptance bounds pre-specified and documented prior to unblinding of experimental data.",
      "rationale": "Pre-specified acceptance bounds (E/uval < 1.96, percentage difference < 10%) documented in the validation plan prior to data unblinding. E/uval values: stiffness 1.41, yield force 1.18, force at 40 mm 1.62 — all within bounds. Percentage differences: 4.7%, 3.2%, 8.1% — all within bounds. Formal statistical comparison using pooled experimental uncertainty (inter-laboratory + within-lab). Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected for validation are directly relevant to the clinical performance metrics and regulatory decision.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three primary performance metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and cited in FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. Each QoI maps directly to a clinical failure mode (excessive flexibility, permanent deformation, catastrophic fracture). Gradation 3 achieved — direct traceability from QoI to regulatory requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities replicate the geometry, loading, and boundary conditions of the COU with documented similarity arguments for any differences.",
      "rationale": "Validation constructs use the identical screw design (non-cannulated 7.5 mm, same revision), identical rod diameter (5.5 mm Ti-6Al-4V), and ASTM F1717 test configuration that is the subject of the regulatory submission. Two independent laboratories provide inter-laboratory reproducibility evidence. The validation domain fully encompasses the COU domain. Gradation 3 achieved."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors have been formally assessed. All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) pass the pre-specified acceptance bounds (E/uval < 1.96; percentage difference < 10%). The Test conditions factor achieved Gradation 2 against a required level of 3, which is noted as a limitation; however, the assessment team determined that the single-condition testing is representative of the regulatory submission scope and that inter-laboratory replication at N=11 provides sufficient confidence. The Numerical solver error factor was not assessed on the basis that commercial solver maturity renders it inapplicable — this determination has not been formally substantiated as a 'not-applicable' scoping decision, and the factor remains in a not-assessed state. The overall credibility evidence is judged sufficient to support a Medium assurance level decision for this Class II device at modelRiskLevel 3.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
